    <title>Brainstorming how neighborhood power grids could work with community mesh networks</title>
    <link>http://commotionwireless.net/fr/blog/brainstorming-how-neighborhood-power-grids-could-work-community-mesh-networks</link>
    <description>&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot; property=&quot;content:encoded&quot;&gt; &lt;p&gt;A community wireless network can provide a reliable conduit for many types of communication. We might initially think of this communication within a human context — sharing music with your friend across town, spreading news to your city about an upcoming event, responding to an emergency, or asking questions of a local politician on a discussion forum. But, in a world that runs parallel to the Internet we use everyday, our communication networks are used by all sorts of machines to make our society an exponentially more productive and automated place.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
